ğŸ” var vs let vs const in JavaScript

Scope:

var â Function-scoped

let â Block-scoped (within {})

const â Block-scoped (within {})

Hoisting:

var â Hoisted and initialized as undefined

let â Hoisted but NOT initialized (accessing before declaration throws ReferenceError)

const â Hoisted but NOT initialized (accessing before declaration throws ReferenceError)

Reassignment:

var â Allowed âœ…

let â Allowed âœ…

const â Not allowed âŒ (you can't reassign it)

Redeclaration:

var â Allowed âœ…

let â Not allowed âŒ

const â Not allowed âŒ

Use Case:

var â Old/legacy JavaScript code (not recommended)

let â Use when the value needs to change

const â Use when the value should not change (best practice)


// var is function-scoped
    function demoVar() {
        if (true) {
          var x = 10;
        }
        console.log(x); // âœ… Works because x is function-scoped
      }
      demoVar();

// let is block-scoped
    function demoLet() {
        if (true) {
        let y = 20;
        }
        console.log(y); // âŒ Error: y is not accessible outside the block
    }
    demoLet();

// const can't be reassigned
    const PI = 3.1416;
    PI = 3.14; // âŒ Error: Cannot reassign a const variable

// const allows mutation of objects
    const user = { name: "Harsha" };
    user.name = "Sree"; // âœ… Allowed (youâ€™re not reassigning, just changing a property)


ğŸ§  Summary:
Use let when the value will change.    
Use const for values that stay constant (default choice).
Avoid var â€” it's old school and may cause bugs due to function scope.